<h2>The Rush Trilogy, Reimagined for PC</h2>

Sonic Rush Rerun goes beyond a simple remake. Instead of recreating the DS original level-for-level, Team Rerun redesigned every stage from scratch to work on a <strong>single widescreen display</strong> — solving the fundamental challenge of adapting a dual-screen game for PC. The result feels familiar yet fresh, with level layouts that blend elements from Rush, Rush Adventure, and Colors DS into something new.

<center style="margin:28px 0"><iframe title="Sonic Rush Rerun Gameplay Trailer" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/KSetMJKUnHo" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></center>

The low-poly 2.5D art style gives the game a distinctive look that translates surprisingly well to HD screens. Character models are expressive with smooth, almost elastic animations — Sonic's running cycle and Blaze's flame effects have been particularly praised by the community. Add <strong>native 144hz+ support</strong> on top of that, and the gameplay feels remarkably fluid on modern monitors. The menus deserve a mention too: every screen features animated character renders and stylized transitions that set the tone before you even start a level.

<h2>Sonic & Blaze — Two Distinct Playstyles</h2>

Both characters play through the same stages but offer genuinely different approaches to each level:

<div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:12px;margin:20px 0 32px">
